Startup culture cannot break the laws of thermodynamics

Oh hi, I=E2=80=99m Paul Jarvis <https://pjrvs.com>. You=E2=80=99re getting =
this email
because you signed up for the Sunday Dispatches, a weekly newsletter on
working and living online. I appreciate you being here, but if you=E2=80=99=
d like
to leave, simply unsubscribe
<https://pjrvs.us6.list-manage.com/unsubscribe?u=3D26857d08cfc91db6993e0bfc=
4&id=3D3f954190de&e=3D55f60dd98f&c=3D8df64abf31>.


A very popular startup person has this tweet pinned to their profile:

*"In startups, if you take your foot off the pedal, the default mode is
reverse, not neutral."*

Which is nothing new for startup culture. I=E2=80=99ve heard this over and =
over for
decades now. It=E2=80=99s the singular, tunnel-vision type of bullshit thin=
king
that=E2=80=99s become and stayed popular.

And the replies (there are pages of them) on that tweet are basically
re-enforcing this narrow view. But then again, that=E2=80=99s what social m=
edia is,
right? Finding people who agree with whatever views you hold, so they can
confirm back at you that your views are correct.

This is why I=E2=80=99ve never fit in with (or cared about) mainstream star=
tup
culture. I think it=E2=80=99s completely asinine to assume that you have to=
 move at
break-neck speed if you want to achieve anything.

I like to move slowly. Methodically. With careful consideration of my every
step, to ensure that it=E2=80=99s the correct step. Sure, it feels a little
=E2=80=9Cover-thinky=E2=80=9D, but I always want to consider the fact that =
my views could
be wrong. And if they are (uh=E2=80=A6 when they are), how could being wron=
g cause
harm?

This =E2=80=9Cthe hustle is everything=E2=80=9D culture is simply an option=
al add-on to the
startup world, and one that I think turns some smart folks away. The folks
who don=E2=80=99t want to sleep at their desks, or always be on, or work 10=
0 hours
a week, or sacrifice everything in the hope that a bet pays off. I think
this also has the potential to put off people who actually have lives they
care about outside of work (kids, partners, friends, etc).

Starting a company is like having an electric car. Sure, it can go super
fucking fast, but it also needs to recharge. If you don=E2=80=99t charge it=
, it
doesn=E2=80=99t go at all. Both things are useful (going fast is exhilarati=
ng, but
charging is required). It feels like too many startups and even the media
that covers them assume they are EVs with perpetual motion machines (note:
these don=E2=80=99t actually exist and violate the first and second laws of
thermodynamics!). The first concept to grasp about the theory of perpetual
motion is that it=E2=80=99s theoretically impossible. Science is fun.

The recharging aspect of starting a company shouldn't be optional. It
doesn=E2=80=99t cause harm or move your work backwards, it helps you move f=
orward
smarter.

Obviously there=E2=80=99s the mental health side of it being hard to sustai=
n ALL
OUT SPEED and keep your sanity and energy levels intact. This, no doubt,
plays into the fact that half of entrepreneurs also deal with depression.

But there=E2=80=99s also the side of taking time to pause to consider what =
we=E2=80=99re
actually doing, especially as new information comes available (as it always
does). Are we making incorrect assumptions? Are we making harmful
assumptions? Do we need the growth we assumed we did? Is the direction
we=E2=80=99re going still one we=E2=80=99re happy with and one that=E2=80=
=99s best for our
customers?

Without the recharge/pause, we barrel forward without thought. This is
lauded as =E2=80=9Cthe way you startup correctly=E2=80=9D. We must move fas=
t and break
things, and only hope those broken things can be fixed later=E2=80=A6

A lot of running and building a startup is learning. About our customers,
about the market, about ourselves. Learning takes time.

Not every successful startup refuses to take their foot off the pedal. Not
every successful startup moves fast and breaks things. There are so many
ways forward that can work, and it=E2=80=99s up to all of us who create and=
 build
to pick the path that will work best and be the least harmful.

At the start, we make assumptions about almost everything, because we need
to (we=E2=80=99re not in the market yet). But then, we start learning and h=
opefully
taking time to digest and adapt based on what we learn.

If we don=E2=80=99t pause to see how best to apply that learning, we can en=
d up
making painful, harmful and expensive mistakes. This is a move in reverse.
If we don=E2=80=99t take our foot off the pedal sometimes, we can=E2=80=99t=
 recharge. And
then we risk running out of the power and insight to move forward at all.

Slow and steady,
PJ

